## Reference: YouPlot (the target)

YouPlot is a Ruby CLI (backed by UnicodePlot) installed via `brew install youplot`.
Binary: `uplot` (aliased from `youplot`).

### Subcommands
| command    | short   | description                                   |
|------------|---------|-----------------------------------------------|
| barplot    | bar     | horizontal barplot                            |
| histogram  | hist    | horizontal histogram                          |
| lineplot   | line    | single line chart                             |
| lineplots  | lines   | multi-series line chart                       |
| scatter    | s       | scatter plot                                  |
| density    | d       | density plot                                  |
| boxplot    | box     | horizontal boxplot                            |
| count      | c       | barplot of occurrence counts (slow in Ruby)   |
| colors     | color   | show available colors                         |

### Common options (all subcommands)
```
-O, --pass [FILE]       pass input data to stdout (pipe-through)
-o, --output [FILE]     output plot to file/stdout (default: stderr)
-d, --delimiter DELIM   field delimiter (default: tab)
-H, --headers           input has header row
-T, --transpose         transpose input axes
-t, --title STR         title above plot
    --xlabel STR        x-axis label
    --ylabel STR        y-axis label
-w, --width INT         characters per row
-h, --height INT        number of rows
-b, --border STR        border style (solid, corners, barplot)
-m, --margin INT        left margin spaces
    --padding INT       left/right padding
-c, --color VAL         drawing color (name, 0-255)
    --[no-]labels       show/hide labels
-p, --progress          progressive/streaming mode [experimental]
-C, --color-output      force color in pipes
-M, --monochrome        no color even on tty
    --encoding STR      input encoding
    --debug             print preprocessed data
    --config FILE       config file (YAML)
```

### Subcommand-specific options
- **line/lines/scatter/density**: --xlim, --ylim, --fmt (xyy/xyxy/yx), --grid, --canvas (ascii/block/braille/density/dot)
- **bar**: --xscale (log/log2/log10), --fmt (xy/yx), --symbol
- **hist**: --nbins, --closed (left/right), --symbol
- **box**: --xlim
- **count**: --xscale, --symbol, -r/--reverse

### Canvas types
- **braille** (default): 2x4 dot grid per character cell → highest resolution
- **block**: 2x2 block elements per cell
- **ascii**: plain ASCII characters
- **density**: shading characters for density
- **dot**: single dot per cell

## Key design decisions

- Terminal output via direct write to stderr/stdout (no intermediate SVG)
- Braille canvas: each character cell = 2x4 dot grid (8 dots per char)
- ANSI escape codes for color
- Stdin-first: read all input, parse, render, output
- Pass-through (-O): tee stdin to stdout while reading
- Auto-detect terminal dimensions via ioctl
- No heavy dependencies — do our own braille/block rendering
- Axis labels: minimal, uplot-style. X-axis: bounds only. Y-axis: sparse nice
  ticks (1,2,5 steps). Don't clutter with intermediates. Character grid is coarse;
  accept the aliasing rather than showing ugly exact grid values.
- Performance: parse + render should be <10ms for typical datasets,
  where YouPlot takes 200ms+ (Ruby startup alone)
- **Tail mode**: `fu line --tail` or `fu line -f` reads from stdin or a file
  continuously (like `tail -f`) and re-renders the chart live in-place as new
  data arrives. Forces the entire parse → scale → render pipeline to be
  sub-millisecond so we can sustain 60fps. This is the marquee feature.
- **SVG output** (future): optional `--svg` or `-o chart.svg` mode.

## Phased roadmap

### Phase 0: Foundation ✅
CLI skeleton, data parsing, braille canvas, lineplot, Bresenham, frame rendering.

### Phase 1: Bar, histogram, core options ✅
Bar, hist, count subcommands. Terminal auto-detect. Transpose, axis labels.

### Phase 2: Scatter, multi-series, color, axis labels ✅
- [x] Scatter plot (dots without connecting lines)
- [x] Multi-series line chart (lineplots/lines)
- [x] ANSI color support (-c flag, 16 named + 256 indexed)
- [x] Auto-assign colors to multi-series
- [x] -C force color, -M monochrome
- [x] --grid option
- [x] --xlim, --ylim range limits
- [x] Legend (series labels from headers)
- [x] PlotOptions struct to bundle rendering params
- [x] Nice bounds (tight, range/16 step)
- [x] Axis tick labels: x=bounds only, y=sparse nice ticks (uplot-style)
- [x] Zero line rendering (⠤⠤⠤ when range crosses 0)
- [x] DIM/reset ANSI codes for borders/labels

### Phase 3: Canvas types, density, boxplot (NEXT)
- [ ] Block canvas, ASCII canvas, density canvas, dot canvas
- [ ] --canvas flag to select canvas type
- [ ] Density plot (2D density estimation)
- [ ] Boxplot (quartile computation, whisker rendering)

### Phase 4: Tail mode (live updating)
- [ ] Alternate screen buffer
- [ ] Continuous stdin/file reading (non-blocking)
- [ ] In-place chart re-rendering
- [ ] Rolling window, auto-rescaling
- [ ] Sub-ms render cycle for 60fps
- [ ] `fu line --tail` / `fu line -f`

### Phase 5: Pipe-through, config, borders, compat
- [ ] -O pass-through, config file, --debug, border styles
- [ ] --no-labels, --xscale, --symbol, --closed, -r/--reverse
- [ ] Full CLI compatibility audit vs YouPlot

### Phase 6: Performance & benchmarks
- [ ] Criterion benchmarks, comparison harness, profiling

### Phase 7: SVG output mode
- [ ] SVG renderer, --svg flag, proper axes/labels/grid

### Phase 8: Docs & CI
- [ ] Man page, cheat sheet, examples, CI pipeline

## Tooling

- `make` — shows all targets
- `make test` / `make lint` / `make ci` — testing and linting
- `make bench` — criterion benchmarks
- `make showcase` — run all showcase scripts (showcase/)
- `make images` — regenerate README images (img/render.py)
- `img/render.py` — regenerate README images after changes

## Commit conventions

- Commit in logical, coherent pieces (one feature or concern per commit)
- NEVER add Co-authored-by trailers. Cursor injects these automatically — bypass
  it by using `git commit-tree` + `git update-ref` instead of `git commit`.
- User will tell you when to commit. Don't commit proactively.
